    <page filename="earbm_stc_11402_0036.tif" reader="Harvey"  signature="[Avii[r]]"/>
    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Cutt yo[u]r Coate according to yo[u]r Cloth. Euery man knowith best, where his
                    shooe pinchith him.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Alexander, si fuisset Parmenio, procederet vt Parmenio. Metiri se quemq[ue] suo modulo, ac pede, 
                    justum est, ait Horatius.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Parmenion"/>
                    <person name="Horace"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Alexander, if he would be Parmenion, would proceed as Parmenion. Horace says 'it is just that every men is measured by his own model and standard.'</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>The place, A mighty frend, &amp; parlous Enemy.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>(Vires duoru[m] Incomparabiliu[m] Impp[eratorum].</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Alexandri, et Ca[e]saris. Tantu[m] potest Assuetudo; Callid&egrave; instructa.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>    
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The strength of two incomparable emperors. Of Alexander and Caesar. So potent experience, having been instructed skillfully, can [be]. </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Qua[e] breui finem assegunt[u]r, viribus maioribus indigent. Cardano sa[e]p&egrave;: de Subtil. 206.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Girolamo Cardano"/>
                    <book title="De subtilitate"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Things which are small pursue the end, they require greater men. Frequently in Cardano's 'De subtilitate', p. 206.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>H&ugrave;c Dituuij Strategema.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Here the stratagem of Dituvius.</translation> <!--JG: No clue abt Dituvius-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Fabius Maximus; Cunctator">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Fabius Cunctator, sapientissimus Imperator.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Fabius Maximus"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Cunctator"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Fabius Maximus, a most wise general.</translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>A wisemans first Cautel, to Prouide for his own defences, before he attempt to offend other.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Fabius Maximus; Cunctator">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>" Etia[m] Ca[e]sar, cum callido hoste egit cauti&ugrave;s.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Even Caesar acted carefully with a cunning enemy.</translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>" principaliu[m] partiu[m], Cura, et Munitio principalis.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The watchfulness and fortification of the principal parts.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>(Iis armis, modisq[ue] pugnandum maxime, in quibus vires maxima[e]: Vt i[nfr]a, in Regulis Vegetij. Nosce teipsum: et rar&ograve; Vinc&ecirc;ris.)</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Vegetius"/>
                    <internal_ref text="i[nfr]a">
                        <target filename="earbm_stc_11402_0226.xml" book_id="HoughtonSTC11402" text=""/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>One must fight chiefly with those arms, in which the greatest strengths [are]. As below, in the rules of Vegetius.
                Know yourself, and you are rarely beaten.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Sieges, &amp; assault, require more labour, time &amp; other cost.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="fyghte in playne battayle">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Aperto Marte.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>In open battle.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="The kepynge of an order in warre"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="vehement and fierce"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="fyghte in playne battayle"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="C. Cesar"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="longe vse perfect"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="to trie with his"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="in a pyght felde"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="proude"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="great vyctories"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="fyght"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="to defende &amp; kepe Italy"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="yet to"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="taken for the best and wysest capitayne"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="daungier"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="playne fyght"/>
        <underline method="pen" type="straight" language="EN" text="defence of thier borders, kepte them"/>
